Replication of “How Will I Be Remembered? Conserving the Environment for the Sake of One’s Legacy” by Zaval, Markowitz & Weber (2015, Psychological Science)

Rhia Catapano

Introduction

Although encouraging pro-environmental behaviors is extremely important to the future, there are a number of psychological barriers that can prevent pro-environmental behaviors. Specifically, the long time horizon and psychological distance serve as barriers to this important goal. The current paper looks to leverage these elements of pro-environmental behavior into opportunities, rather than barriers.

Specifically, the paper finds that priming legacy motives increased donations to an environmental charity, proenvironmental intentions, and climate change beliefs. To prime legacy motives, participants write about what they want to be remembered for by future generations. This increases motivation to leave a positive legacy, which in turn increases pro-environmental behaviors. Therefore, this paper uses a simple intervention to leverage a major barrier in environmental behavior (future-focused and distant) into an opportunity to encourage these behaviors.

Methods

Power Analysis

The original study reports cohen’s d’s ranging from 0.23 to 0.36 on the various measures used (legacy motives, climate change beliefs, behavioral intentions, and donation measure). Therefore, I’ve assumed a cohen’s d of 0.23, to be conservative. The standard deviation for most of the measures is approximately 1.

power.t.test(delta=0.23, sd=1, power=.95, sig.level=0.05)

Planned Sample

The original paper uses a sample size of about 300 participants, based on the estimated effect size from a pilot test. This is the most feasible number of participants that will not severely underpower the study.

Materials & Procedure

Writing activity Participants will be randomly assigned to one of two conditions. As per the original experiment, “In the legacy condition, participants began by writing a short essay describing what they want to be remembered for by future generations…The essay-writing task was omitted in the control condition, which otherwise followed the same procedure as the legacy condition.” The writing task will be copied verbatim from the project’s supplemental materials online.

Environmental Behaviors As per the original experiment, “Participants next answered two sets of questions, one assessing their beliefs about climate change and the other their willingness to take proenvironmental action. Climate-change beliefs were measured using the average score of four randomly ordered items (α = .88; e.g., “I feel a responsibility to reduce my personal contribution to climate change”). Participants responded to each statement on a 7-point scale ranging from 1 (strongly disagree) to 7 (strongly agree). Similarly, proenvironmental behavioral intentions were measured using the average score of six items that asked participants how often they intend to perform actions to help mitigate climate change over the next month (α = .76; e.g., “Buy green products instead of regular products”); responses were made on a scale from 1 (never) to 6 (all the time).

Manipulation Check - Legacy Motives Following the original experiment, “This measure consisted of the average score of three items relating to legacy motives (α = .82): (a) “It is important to me to leave a positive legacy,” (b) “It is important for me to leave a positive mark on society,” and (c) “I care about what future generations think of me.” Participants indicated the extent to which each statement described them on a scale from 1 (not at all) to 6 (a great amount). This legacy-motives scale was placed at the end of the survey…”

The control condition is available online at: http://stanford.edu/~rhiac/Psych254/legacy_proj_control.html

The legacy prime condition is available online at: http://stanford.edu/~rhiac/Psych254/legacy_proj_prime.html

Analysis Plan

As per the original paper, no participants will be excluded from analysis. In addition, although additional analysis was performed controlling for a range of demographic variables (to show the robustness of the finding), the original analysis examines the effect of condition on the various DV’s, without controlling for demographic variables.

Linear regressions will be performed to examine the effect of the legacy prime on legacy motives, climate change beliefs, and behavioral intentions.

In addition, mediation analysis will be conducted using both a sobel’s z test, and using bootstrapping as suggested by Preacher & Hayes, 2008, with 5,000 samples. Specifically, it is predicted that legacy motives mediates the relationship between condition (legacy prime/no legacy prime) and both climate change attitudes and intentions.

Differences from Original Study

In the original study, all participants were paid the same amount. However, in this study, we will pay a base rate of $0.20, and an additional bonus of $0.40 to the people in the legacy motives priming condition (ie. the people who write the 4 minute essay).

In addition, in the original study the average time taken to write the essay was 6.5 minutes. However, we will be shortening the essay writing task to 4 minutes instead. In addition, a 20 word minumum was imposed on the essay task before submission was allowed. There was no countdown indicator, but participants were asked to write more if they tried to submit an essay with under 20 words.

Finally, in the original study, an additional DV was included, donation to an environmental charity. Given that this DV shows the same trend as the other DV’s being measured, this DV will be excluded from the present replication.

Data preparation

Read in the data from .json files, and format into a dataframe.

path <- "~/Desktop/2016_Winter/Stats_254/Project/rhiacProject/replication_report/"
files <- dir(paste0(path,"sandbox-results"), 
             pattern = "*.json")
d.raw <- data.frame(stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for (f in files) {
jf <- paste0(path, "/sandbox-results/", f)
jd <- fromJSON(file=jf)

cols <- which(jd$answers$data$trial_number_block != 0)

id <- data.frame(workerid = jd$WorkerId, 
                totalTime = jd$answers$data$totalTime,
                totalHiddenTime = jd$answers$data$totalHiddenTime,
                condition = jd$answers$data$condition,
                trialNum = jd$answers$data$trial_number_block[cols],
                trialType = jd$answers$data$trial_type[cols],
                sentence = jd$answers$data$sentence[cols],
                rating = jd$answers$data$rating, 
                environmentalist =
                  ifelse(is.null(unlist(jd$answers$data$environmentalist)),NA,
                                          unlist(jd$answers$data$environmentalist)),
                legacy_essay = jd$answers$data$legacy_essay,
                sex = 
                  ifelse(is.null(unlist(jd$answers$data$sex)), NA, 
                         unlist(jd$answers$data$sex)), 
                race = 
                  ifelse(is.null(unlist(jd$answers$data$race)), NA,
                         unlist(jd$answers$data$race)),
                year = jd$answers$data$year,
                grandparent =
                  ifelse(is.null(unlist(jd$answers$data$grandparent)),NA,
                         unlist(jd$answers$data$grandparent)),
                children = 
                  ifelse(is.null(unlist(jd$answers$data$children)),NA,
                         unlist(jd$answers$data$children)),
                stringsAsFactors=FALSE)

d.raw <- bind_rows(d.raw, id)
}


# Number of participants
n = length(unique(d.raw$workerid))

The 3 DV’s are ratings on the behavioral intentions trials, ratings on the environmental attitudes trials, and ratings on the legacy motives trials. The indexes for each are computed as the average of the ratings for the items that make up the composite index.

trial_index <- d.raw %>%
 group_by(workerid, trialType) %>%
 summarize("index"=mean(as.numeric(rating)), "condition" = condition[1], "year"=year[1], "sex"=sex[1], "environmentalist" = environmentalist[1], "race" = race[1], "year" = year[1], "grandparent" = grandparent[1], "children" = children[1])

d <- spread(trial_index, trialType, index)
d <- d %>%
  rename(beh_int_index = beh_int_trial,
         env_att_index = env_att,
         leg_mot_index = legacy_motives2)

d$condition <- factor(d$condition, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("control", "leg_prime"))
d$sex <- as.factor(d$sex)
d$environmentalist <- as.factor(d$environmentalist)
d$race <- as.factor(d$race)
d$grandparent <- as.factor(d$grandparent)
d$children <- as.factor(x = d$children)

Main Effects from Paper

Effect of legacy prime on legacy motives

The original paper reports that, “As expected, the essay manipulation successfully enhanced overall legacy motives. Almost 10 min after being exposed to the manipulation, participants who wrote the essay reported higher legacy motives (M = 4.47, SD = 1.06), compared with those in the control con- dition (M = 4.19, SD = 1.05), F(1, 310) = 5.64, p = .018, Cohen’s d = 0.27.”

model <- lm(leg_mot_index ~ condition, d)

Effect of legacy prime on environmental behavior intentions

The original paper reports: “Moreover, as predicted, we found a significant effect of the legacy prime on willingness to engage in behaviors aimed at combating climate change. Participants who were primed with legacy motives had higher belief scores (M = 5.39, SD = 1.08) than those in the control condition (M = 5.11, SD = 1.27), F(1, 309) = 4.08, p = .040, d = 0.23.”

Effect of legacy prime on beliefs/attitudes

The original paper reports: “We also found a significant effect of the legacy prime on behavioral intentions. Participants who were primed reported greater behavioral intentions (M = 3.05, SD = 0.86) than those who were not primed (M=2.73,SD=0.85), F(1,309)=10.07, p=.002, d=0.36.”

Mediation Analysis

Path 1: Prime -> Legacy Motives -> Attitudes

The original paper reports: “To confirm that the influence of the legacy prime on climate-change attitudes was driven by increases in legacy motives, we conducted a mediation analysis using the mean legacy-motives score as a mediator. The effect of the legacy prime on individuals’ climate-change beliefs was fully mediated by increases in legacy motives—direct effect of the priming condition on beliefs: t(308) = 2.01; effect of priming condition on beliefs, mediated by legacy motives: t(308) = 1.29, Sobel’s z = 2.19, p = .028. Mediation was also confirmed by a bias-corrected bootstrapping procedure using 5,000 samples (Preacher & Hayes, 2008; see Median Test in the Supplemental Material). This analysis showed that the indirect effect of the legacy prime on climate-change beliefs through legacy motives was significant, with a 95% confidence interval (CI) that excluded zero (β = 0.041, 95% CI = [0.01, 0.09], p = .029).”

Path 2: Prime -> Legacy Motives -> Behavioral Intentions

The original paper reports: “When we replaced climate-change attitudes with behavioral intentions as the outcome variable, behavioral intentions were also partially mediated by increases in legacy motives—direct effect of priming condition on intentions: t(311) = 3.17, effect of priming condition on beliefs, mediated by leg- acy motives: t(311) = 2.65, Sobel’s z = 2.11, p = .034; the indirect effect was significant (β = 0.034, 95% CI = [0.01, 0.08], p = .035).”
